## 3  Trait Cheat-Sheet
### 3.1  `ToolExecutor`
```rust
async fn execute(&self, params: Self::Params, tool_call_id: String) -> Result<Self::Output>;
```
Called **once** after params are fully available. Should be pure business logic.

### 3.2  `StreamingToolExecutor`
Override when you need incremental feedback while JSON is arriving.
Typical implementation pattern:
```rust
async fn ingest_chunk(&mut self, chunk: &str) -> Result<Vec<StreamStage>> { тАж }
async fn finalize(&mut self) -> Result<Vec<StreamStage>> { тАж }
```
Return combinations of:
* `ParamsChunk(Value)`   тАУ raw fragment (we immediately map to UI).
* `ParamsComplete(Value)`тАУ full JSON parsed.
* `OutputComplete(Value)`тАУ serialized output of `execute`.
(We rarely use `OutputChunk` nowadays.)

### 3.3  `ToolStreamer`
Adds two convenience methods:
```rust
async fn ingest_and_send(&mut self, chunk: &str, sender: &mpsc::Sender<UiEvent>)
async fn finalize_and_send(&mut self, sender: &mpsc::Sender<UiEvent>)
```
Implement `map_stage` to convert low-level stages into your `UiEvent` enum or struct.  Most tools use the generic `map_param_chunk` + `StreamSpec` to keep this tiny.

